Math219 Project 1¶

Introduction¶

The dataset used contains more than 90000 professional cricket players all over the world through all timeline scraped from the ESPN official website. Contains 181 columns with unique ID, Description for some and all batting bowling scores from Tests, ODI, List A, First_Class, T20I, T20. This ESPN API was run on a spider and uploaded to dataworld from where I got it. The link:https://data.world/raghav333/cricket-players-espn/workspace/project-summary?agentid=raghav333&datasetid=cricket-players-espn

Preprocessing¶

In [2]:
# Getting all the required columns as I only want to analyse batsmen playing in the test format of cricket.

Cricket = pd.read_csv('SuperCleaned.csv')
columns_to_keep = ['NAME', 'COUNTRY', 'Batting style','BATTING_Tests_Inns','BATTING_Tests_Runs','BATTING_Tests_Ave','BATTING_Tests_100','BATTING_Tests_50']
cricket_cleaned = Cricket[columns_to_keep]
cricket_cleaned.to_csv('cleaned_cricket_dataset.csv', index=False)

#replacing empty spaces with 0 for integer based columns

Cricket1 = pd.read_csv('cleaned_cricket_dataset.csv')
columns_to_fill = ['BATTING_Tests_Inns', 'BATTING_Tests_Runs', 'BATTING_Tests_Ave','BATTING_Tests_100','BATTING_Tests_50']
Cricket1[columns_to_fill] = Cricket1[columns_to_fill].fillna(0)
Cricket1.to_csv('int_cricket.csv', index=False)

#replacing empty spaces with unkown for string based columns

Cricket2 = pd.read_csv('int_cricket.csv')
columns_to_fill1 = ['NAME', 'COUNTRY', 'Batting style']
Cricket2[columns_to_fill1] = Cricket2[columns_to_fill1].fillna("Unkown")
Cricket2.to_csv('string_cricket.csv', index=False)


#only players with atleast 1 innings will be analysed

Cricket3 = pd.read_csv('string_cricket.csv')
Cricket3_cleaned = Cricket3[Cricket3['BATTING_Tests_Inns'] > 0]
Cricket3_cleaned.to_csv('final_cricket_players_dataset.csv', index=False)


print("Final CSV file cleaned and saved successfully!")

# Identifying outliers for the number of test innings batted

Final_Cricket = pd.read_csv('final_cricket_players_dataset.csv')
column_to_analyze = 'BATTING_Tests_Inns'
mean = Final_Cricket[column_to_analyze].mean()
std_dev = Final_Cricket[column_to_analyze].std()
Final_Cricket['z_score'] = np.abs((Final_Cricket[column_to_analyze] - mean) / std_dev)
outliers1 = Final_Cricket[Final_Cricket['z_score'] > 3]
print("Outliers:")
print(outliers1)

#graphical analysis

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
numerical_summary = Final_Cricket.describe()

for col in Final_Cricket.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.histplot(Final_Cricket[col], kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Histogram of {col}')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()


for col in Final_Cricket.select_dtypes(include=['object']):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.countplot(data=Final_Cricket, x=col, palette='viridis')
    plt.title(f'Count plot of {col}')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()

#Correlation between the batting style of players and the avergae runs scored by them per innings

categorical_column = 'Batting style 1'  
numerical_column = 'BATTING_Tests_Ave'  
correlation_coefficient, p_value = pointbiserialr(Final_Cricket[categorical_column], Final_Cricket[numerical_column])
print(f"Point-biserial correlation coefficient: {correlation_coefficient}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

#Correlation between the total number of innings played and the total runs scored by them

column11 = 'BATTING_Tests_Inns' 
column22 = 'BATTING_Tests_Runs'
correlation = Final_Cricket[column11].corr(Final_Cricket[column22])
print(f"The correlation between {column11} and {column22} is: {correlation}")

#Correlation between the centuries scored by the player and the total number of half-centuries scored by them

column1 = 'BATTING_Tests_100'  # Replace 'column1' with the name of your first column
column2 = 'BATTING_Tests_50'  # Replace 'column2' with the name of your second column
correlation = Final_Cricket[column1].corr(Final_Cricket[column2])
print(f"The correlation between {column1} and {column2} is: {correlation}")

Point-biserial correlation coefficient: -0.13946840668457375
P-value: 4.0255533640972264e-17
The correlation between BATTING_Tests_Inns and BATTING_Tests_Runs is: 0.9192781150500975
The correlation between BATTING_Tests_100 and BATTING_Tests_50 is: 0.8931637579565642

For the correlation between the batting style of players and the avergae runs scored by them per innings, the Point-biserial correlation coefficient is negative and close to 0, while P- value is extremely low significantly implying that there is no correlation for whether the player is right handed or left handed with how he performs. This makes sense as itsa purely skill bases sport. For the Correlation between the total number of innings played and the total runs scored by them, the pearson coefficient is almost 1 suggesting a direct linear correlation.This makes sense that more he will play the more runs he can score. For the Correlation between the centuries scored by the player and the total number of half-centuries scored by them, the pearson coefficeint is close to 1 suggestinga linear relationship. This makes sense as if the player has already reached 50 runs , there is a higher probability that he might reach 100 runs.

Discussion¶

1.Does the nationality of the player predict whether the player is successful, as measured by a 1000 total runs in test crikcet? This would help as the more cricket dominated nations will have better facilities and opportunities to train and grow a player as compared to ations dominated by other sports. 2.Does the number of half-centuries,centuries,batting style and country predict the number of innings a player might play in the future? This would help as the team might need Big hiters or left handed players to fill in the gaps in their squad which would translate to more opportunities for those players.
